StreamLAB

The provided binary was tested on Ubuntu 16.10.

We provide the following shell scripts, covering the different scenarios described in the paper:
- run_online.sh uses the short input file traces/trimmed/trace_0.cs with the spec_online.lola and simulates a delay of 1ms between inputs
- run_offline_silent.sh uses the long input file (400k events) traces/timed/trace_0.csv with the spec_offline.lola -- took around 15 seconds on our machine
- run_offline_triggers.sh is the verbose version of run_offline_silent.sh that shows the triggers that fire



USAGE

You can run
$ stream_lab monitor --help
to get an overview of all possible options and flags:
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
USAGE:
    stream_lab.exe monitor [FLAGS] [OPTIONS] <SPEC> <--online|--offline>

FLAGS:
        --offline    Use the timestamps from the input.
                     The column name must be one of [time,timestamp,ts].
                     The column must produce a monotonically increasing sequence of values.
        --online     Use the current system time for timestamps
        --stderr     Output to stderr
        --stdin      Read CSV input from stdin [Default}
        --stdout     Output to stdout
    -h, --help       Prints help information
    -V, --version    Prints version information

OPTIONS:
        --csv-in <CSV_INPUT_FILE>    Read CSV input from a file
    -d, --delay <DELAY>              Delay [ms] between reading in two lines from the input. Only used for file input.
                                     [default: 0]
    -l, --verbosity <VERBOSITY>       [default: triggers]  [possible values: debug, outputs, triggers, warnings, silent]

ARGS:
    <SPEC>    Sets the specification file to use
------------------------------------------------------------------------------


The typical invocation looks like this:
$ stream_lab monitor --offline --csv-in=./path/to/inputs.csv --verbosity=triggers --stdout ./path/to/specification

Constraints:
You must specify either --offline or --online to determine where the timestamps come from.
You must specify either --stdin or --csv-in=./path/to/inputs.csv to determine where the input comes from.
You can choose either --stderr or --stdout to determine where the output should go.
You can specify the verbosity.
You must specify the ./path/to/specification containing a RTLola specification.
If you use --csv-in=<CSV_INPUT_FILE> and --online, you can add --delay=<DELAY> to add an artificial delay between reading in the lines.